[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] Bailey and Piliouras showed that although the time average behavior of multiplicative weights update converges to Nash equilibria in zero-sum games the day-to-day (last iterate) behavior diverges away from it.
[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] In machine learning, Littlestone and Warmuth generalized the winnow algorithm to the weighted majority algorithm.
[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] Later, Freund and Schapire generalized it in the form of hedge algorithm.
[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] AdaBoost Algorithm formulated by Yoav Freund and Robert Schapire also employed the Multiplicative Weight Update Method.
[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] Based on current knowledge in algorithms, the multiplicative weight update method was first used in Littlestone's winnow algorithm.
[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] It is used in machine learning to solve a linear program.
[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] The aim is to find non-negative weights such that for all examples, the sign of the weighted combination of the features matches its labels.
