[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] Without loss of generality, assume the total weight is 1 so that they form a distribution.
[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] The hedge algorithm is similar to the weighted majority algorithm.
[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] However, their exponential update rules are different.
[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] It is generally used to solve the problem of binary allocation in which we need to allocate different portion of resources into N different options.
[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] The loss with every option is available at the end of every iteration.
[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] The goal is to reduce the total loss suffered for a particular allocation.
[src:online-learning-theory/multiplicative-weight-update-method] The allocation for the following iteration is then revised, based on the total loss suffered in the current iteration using multiplicative update.
