[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] Online convex optimization (OCO) is a general framework for decision making which leverages convex optimization to allow for efficient algorithms.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] The goal is to minimize regret, or the difference between cumulative loss and the loss of the best fixed point $u\in S$ in hindsight.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] As an example, consider the case of online least squares linear regression.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] Here, the weight vectors come from the convex set $S=\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , and nature sends back the convex loss function $v_{t}(w)=(\langle w,x_{t}\rangle -y_{t})^{2}$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] Note here that $y_{t}$ is implicitly sent with $v_{t}$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] Some online prediction problems however cannot fit in the framework of OCO.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] For example, in online classification, the prediction domain and the loss functions are not convex.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] In such scenarios, two simple techniques for convexification are used: randomisation and surrogate loss functions .
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] The simplest learning rule to try is to select (at the current step) the hypothesis that has the least loss over all past rounds.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] This algorithm is called Follow the leader, and round t is simply given by: $w_{t}=\mathop {\operatorname {arg\,min} } _{w\in S}\sum _{i=1}^{t-1}v_{i}(w)$ This method can thus be looked as a greedy algorithm.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] For the case of online quadratic optimization (where the loss function is $v_{t}(w)=\left\|w-x_{t}\right\|_{2}^{2}$ ), one can show a regret bound that grows as $\log(T)$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] However, similar bounds cannot be obtained for the FTL algorithm for other important families of models like online linear optimization.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] To do so, one modifies FTL by adding regularisation.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] This is a natural modification of FTL that is used to stabilise the FTL solutions and obtain better regret bounds.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] Suppose the regularisation function ${\textstyle R(w)={\frac {1}{2\eta }}\left\|w\right\|_{2}^{2}}$ is chosen for some positive number $\eta$ .
