[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] It is also known as Nesterov's dual averaging algorithm.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] In this scenario of linear loss functions and quadratic regularisation, the regret is bounded by $O({\sqrt {T}})$ , and thus the average regret goes to 0 as desired.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] The above proved a regret bound for linear loss functions $v_{t}(w)=\langle w,z_{t}\rangle$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] Quadratically regularised FTRL algorithms lead to lazily projected gradient algorithms as described above.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] To use the above for arbitrary convex functions and regularisers, one uses online mirror descent.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] The optimal regularization in hindsight can be derived for linear loss functions, this leads to the AdaGrad algorithm.
