[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] Continual learning means constantly improving the learned model by processing continuous streams of information.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] Continual learning capabilities are essential for software systems and autonomous agents interacting in an ever changing real world.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] However, continual learning is a challenge for machine learning and neural network models since the continual acquisition of incrementally available information from non-stationary data distributions generally leads to catastrophic forgetting.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] The paradigm of online learning has different interpretations depending on the choice of the learning model, each of which has distinct implications about the predictive quality of the sequence of functions $f_{1},f_{2},\ldots ,f_{n}$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] The prototypical stochastic gradient descent algorithm is used for this discussion.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] The first interpretation consider the stochastic gradient descent method as applied to the problem of minimizing the expected risk $I[w]$ defined above.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] This interpretation is also valid in the case of a finite training set; although with multiple passes through the data the gradients are no longer independent, still complexity results can be obtained in special cases.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] The second interpretation applies to the case of a finite training set and considers the SGD algorithm as an instance of incremental gradient descent method.
[src:online-learning-theory/online-machine-learning] Since this interpretation concerns the empirical risk and not the expected risk, multiple passes through the data are readily allowed and actually lead to tighter bounds on the deviations $I_{n}[w_{t}]-I_{n}[w_{n}^{\ast }]$ , where $w_{n}^{\ast }$ is the minimizer of $I_{n}[w]$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In machine learning, the **perceptron** is an algorithm for supervised learning of binary classifiers.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] A binary classifier is a function that can decide whether or not an input, represented by a vector of numbers, belongs to some specific class.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] It is a type of linear classifier, i.e. a classification algorithm that makes its predictions based on a linear predictor function combining a set of weights with the feature vector.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The artificial neuron and artificial neural network were invented in 1943 by Warren McCulloch and Walter Pitts in their seminal paper "A Logical Calculus of the Ideas Immanent in Nervous Activity".
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In 1957, Frank Rosenblatt was at the Cornell Aeronautical Laboratory.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] He simulated the perceptron on an IBM 704.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Being more interested in hardware implementations, he obtained funding by the Information Systems Branch of the United States Office of Naval Research and the Rome Air Development Center, to build a custom-made analog computer, the Mark I Perceptron.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Rosenblatt's team assembled and tested it at the Cornell Aeronautical Laboratory (CAL) in Buffalo, NY, USA between June 1959 and December 14, 1959.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Its first public demonstration took place on 23 June 1960.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The machine was "part of a previously secret four-year NPIC [the US' National Photographic Interpretation Center] effort from 1963 through 1966 to develop this algorithm into a useful tool for photo-interpreters".
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Rosenblatt described the details of the perceptron in a 1958 paper.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] His organization of a perceptron is constructed of three kinds of cells ("units"): S, A, R, which stand for "sensory", "association" and "response".
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] He presented at the first international symposium on AI, *Mechanisation of Thought Processes*, which took place in 1958 November.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Rosenblatt's project was funded under Contract Nonr-401(40) "Cognitive Systems Research Program", which lasted from 1959 to 1970, and Contract Nonr-2381(00) "Project PARA" ("PARA" means "Perceiving and Recognition Automata"), which lasted from 1957 to 1963.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In 1959, the Institute for Defense Analysis awarded his group a $10,000 contract.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] By September 1961, the ONR awarded further $153,000 worth of contracts, with $108,000 committed for 1962.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The ONR research manager, Marvin Denicoff, stated that ONR, instead of ARPA, funded the Perceptron project, because the project was unlikely to produce technological results in the near or medium term.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Funding from ARPA go up to the order of millions dollars, while from ONR are on the order of 10,000 dollars.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Meanwhile, the head of IPTO at ARPA, J.C.R.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Licklider, was interested in 'self-organizing', 'adaptive' and other biologically-inspired methods in the 1950s; but by the mid-1960s he was openly critical of these, including the perceptron.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Instead he strongly favored the logical AI approach of Simon and Newell.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The perceptron was intended to be a machine, rather than a program, and while its first implementation was in software for the IBM 704, it was subsequently implemented in custom-built hardware as the Mark I Perceptron with the project name "Project PARA", designed for image recognition.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The machine is currently in Smithsonian National Museum of American History.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Rosenblatt called this three-layered perceptron network the *alpha-perceptron*, to distinguish it from other perceptron models he experimented with.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The S-units are connected to the A-units randomly (according to a table of random numbers) via a plugboard (see photo), to "eliminate any particular intentional bias in the perceptron".
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The connection weights are fixed, not learned.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Rosenblatt was adamant about the random connections, as he believed the retina was randomly connected to the visual cortex, and he wanted his perceptron machine to resemble human visual perception.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The A-units are connected to the R-units, with adjustable weights encoded in potentiometers, and weight updates during learning were performed by electric motors.The hardware details are in an operators' manual.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The Photo Division of Central Intelligence Agency, from 1960 to 1964, studied the use of Mark I Perceptron machine for recognizing militarily interesting silhouetted targets (such as planes and ships) in aerial photos.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Rosenblatt described his experiments with many variants of the Perceptron machine in a book *Principles of Neurodynamics* (1962).
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The book is a published version of the 1961 report.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The machine was shipped from Cornell to Smithsonian in 1967, under a government transfer administered by the Office of Naval Research.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Although the perceptron initially seemed promising, it was quickly proved that perceptrons could not be trained to recognise many classes of patterns.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] This caused the field of neural network research to stagnate for many years, before it was recognised that a feedforward neural network with two or more layers (also called a multilayer perceptron) had greater processing power than perceptrons with one layer (also called a single-layer perceptron).
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Single-layer perceptrons are only capable of learning linearly separable patterns.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] For a classification task with some step activation function, a single node will have a single line dividing the data points forming the patterns.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] More nodes can create more dividing lines, but those lines must somehow be combined to form more complex classifications.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] A second layer of perceptrons, or even linear nodes, are sufficient to solve many otherwise non-separable problems.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In 1969, a famous book entitled *Perceptrons* by Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert showed that it was impossible for these classes of network to learn an XOR function.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] It is often incorrectly believed that they also conjectured that a similar result would hold for a multi-layer perceptron network.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] However, this is not true, as both Minsky and Papert already knew that multi-layer perceptrons were capable of producing an XOR function.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] (See the page on *Perceptrons (book)* for more information.) Nevertheless, the often-miscited Minsky and Papert text caused a significant decline in interest and funding of neural network research.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] It took ten more years until neural network research experienced a resurgence in the 1980s.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] This text was reprinted in 1987 as "Perceptrons - Expanded Edition" where some errors in the original text are shown and corrected.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Rosenblatt continued working on perceptrons despite diminishing funding.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The last attempt was Tobermory, built between 1961 and 1967, built for speech recognition.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] It had 4 layers with 12,000 weights implemented by toroidal magnetic cores.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] By the time of its completion, simulation on digital computers had become faster than purpose-built perceptron machines.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The kernel perceptron algorithm was already introduced in 1964 by Aizerman et al.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Margin bounds guarantees were given for the Perceptron algorithm in the general non-separable case first by Freund and Schapire (1998), and more recently by Mohri and Rostamizadeh (2013) who extend previous results and give new and more favorable L1 bounds.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The perceptron is a simplified model of a biological neuron.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] While the complexity of biological neuron models is often required to fully understand neural behavior, research suggests a perceptron-like linear model can produce some behavior seen in real neurons.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The solution spaces of decision boundaries for all binary functions and learning behaviors are studied in.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The bias shifts the decision boundary away from the origin and does not depend on any input value.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The binary value of $f(\mathbf {x} )$ (0 or 1) is used to perform binary classification on $\mathbf {x}$ as either a positive or a negative instance.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Spatially, the bias shifts the position (though not the orientation) of the planar decision boundary.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In the context of neural networks, a perceptron is an artificial neuron using the Heaviside step function as the activation function.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The perceptron algorithm is also termed the **single-layer perceptron**, to distinguish it from a multilayer perceptron, which is a misnomer for a more complicated neural network.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] As a linear classifier, the single-layer perceptron is the simplest feedforward neural network.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] From an information theory point of view, a single perceptron with *K* inputs has a capacity of *2K* bits of information.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In words, one perceptron unit can almost certainly memorize a random assignment of binary labels on N points when $N\leq 2K$ , but almost certainly not when $N>2K$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] When operating on only binary inputs, a perceptron is called a linearly separable Boolean function, or threshold Boolean function.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The sequence of numbers of threshold Boolean functions on n inputs is OEIS A000609.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The value is only known exactly up to $n=9$ case, but the order of magnitude is known quite exactly: it has upper bound $2^{n^{2}-n\log _{2}n+O(n)}$ and lower bound $2^{n^{2}-n\log _{2}n-O(n)}$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Any Boolean linear threshold function can be implemented with only integer weights.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Furthermore, the number of bits necessary and sufficient for representing a single integer weight parameter is $\Theta (n\ln n)$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] A single perceptron can learn to classify any half-space.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] It cannot solve any linearly nonseparable vectors, such as the Boolean exclusive-or problem (the famous "XOR problem").
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] A perceptron network with **one hidden layer** can learn to classify any compact subset arbitrarily closely.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Similarly, it can also approximate any compactly-supported continuous function arbitrarily closely.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] This is essentially a special case of the theorems by George Cybenko and Kurt Hornik.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Consider a perceptron network with n input units, one hidden layer, and one output, similar to the Mark I Perceptron machine.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] It computes a Boolean function of type $f:2^{n}\to 2$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] They call a function **conjunctively local of order k**, iff there exists a perceptron network such that each unit in the hidden layer connects to at most k input units.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] (Theorem 3.1.1): The parity function is conjunctively local of order n .
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] (Section 5.5): The connectedness function is conjunctively local of order $\Omega (n^{1/2})$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Below is an example of a learning algorithm for a single-layer perceptron with a single output unit.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] For a single-layer perceptron with multiple output units, since the weights of one output unit are completely separate from all the others', the same algorithm can be run for each output unit.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] For multilayer perceptrons, where a hidden layer exists, more sophisticated algorithms such as backpropagation must be used.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] If the activation function or the underlying process being modeled by the perceptron is nonlinear, alternative learning algorithms such as the delta rule can be used as long as the activation function is differentiable.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Nonetheless, the learning algorithm described in the steps below will often work, even for multilayer perceptrons with nonlinear activation functions.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] When multiple perceptrons are combined in an artificial neural network, each output neuron operates independently of all the others; thus, learning each output can be considered in isolation.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] For offline learning, the second step may be repeated until the iteration error ${\frac {1}{s}}\sum _{j=1}^{s}|d_{j}-y_{j}(t)|$ is less than a user-specified error threshold $\gamma$ , or a predetermined number of iterations have been completed, where *s* is again the size of the sample set.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The algorithm updates the weights after every training sample in step 2b, though one may note that the weights remain unchanged whenever $d_{j}=y_{j}(t)$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] A single perceptron is a linear classifier.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] It can only reach a stable state if all input vectors are classified correctly.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In case the training set D is *not* linearly separable, i.e. if the positive examples cannot be separated from the negative examples by a hyperplane, then the algorithm would not converge since there is no solution.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Hence, if linear separability of the training set is not known a priori, one of the training variants below should be used.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Detailed analysis and extensions to the convergence theorem are in Chapter 11 of *Perceptrons* (1969).
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Linear separability is testable in time $\min(O(n^{d/2}),O(d^{2n}),O(n^{d-1}\ln n))$ , where n is the number of data points, and d is the dimension of each point.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] If the training set *is* linearly separable, then the perceptron is guaranteed to converge after making finitely many mistakes.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The theorem is proved by Rosenblatt et al.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Then the perceptron 0-1 learning algorithm converges after making at most ${\textstyle (R/\gamma )^{2}}$ mistakes, for any learning rate, and any method of sampling from the dataset.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The following simple proof is due to Novikoff (1962).
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The idea of the proof is that the weight vector is always adjusted by a bounded amount in a direction with which it has a negative dot product, and thus can be bounded above by *O*(√*t*), where t is the number of changes to the weight vector.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] However, it can also be bounded below by *O*(*t*) because if there exists an (unknown) satisfactory weight vector, then every change makes progress in this (unknown) direction by a positive amount that depends only on the input vector.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Suppose at step ${\textstyle t}$ , the perceptron with weight ${\textstyle w_{t}}$ makes a mistake on data point ${\textstyle (x,y)}$ , then it updates to ${\textstyle w_{t+1}=w_{t}+r(y-f_{w_{t}}(x))x}$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] If ${\textstyle y=0}$ , the argument is symmetric, so we omit it.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] While the perceptron algorithm is guaranteed to converge on *some* solution in the case of a linearly separable training set, it may still pick *any* solution and problems may admit many solutions of varying quality.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The *perceptron of optimal stability*, nowadays better known as the linear support-vector machine, was designed to solve this problem (Krauth and Mezard, 1987).
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] When the dataset is not linearly separable, then there is no way for a single perceptron to converge.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Consider a dataset where the x are from $\{-1,+1\}^{n}$ , that is, the vertices of an n-dimensional hypercube centered at origin, and $y=\theta (x_{i})$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] That is, all data points with positive $x_{i}$ have $y=1$ , and vice versa.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] By the perceptron convergence theorem, a perceptron would converge after making at most n mistakes.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] If we were to write a logical program to perform the same task, each positive example shows that one of the coordinates is the right one, and each negative example shows that its *complement* is a positive example.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] By collecting all the known positive examples, we eventually eliminate all but one coordinate, at which point the dataset is learned.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] This bound is asymptotically tight in terms of the worst-case.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In the worst-case, the first presented example is entirely new, and gives n bits of information, but each subsequent example would differ minimally from previous examples, and gives 1 bit each.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] After $n+1$ examples, there are $2n$ bits of information, which is sufficient for the perceptron (with $2n$ bits of information).
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] However, it is not tight in terms of expectation if the examples are presented uniformly at random, since the first would give n bits, the second $n/2$ bits, and so on, taking $O(\ln n)$ examples in total.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The pocket algorithm with ratchet (Gallant, 1990) solves the stability problem of perceptron learning by keeping the best solution seen so far "in its pocket".
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The pocket algorithm then returns the solution in the pocket, rather than the last solution.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] It can be used also for non-separable data sets, where the aim is to find a perceptron with a small number of misclassifications.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] However, these solutions appear purely stochastically and hence the pocket algorithm neither approaches them gradually in the course of learning, nor are they guaranteed to show up within a given number of learning steps.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The Maxover algorithm (Wendemuth, 1995) is "robust" in the sense that it will converge regardless of (prior) knowledge of linear separability of the data set.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In the linearly separable case, it will solve the training problem – if desired, even with optimal stability (maximum margin between the classes).
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] For non-separable data sets, it will return a solution with a computable small number of misclassifications.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In all cases, the algorithm gradually approaches the solution in the course of learning, without memorizing previous states and without stochastic jumps.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Convergence is to global optimality for separable data sets and to local optimality for non-separable data sets.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The Voted Perceptron (Freund and Schapire, 1999), is a variant using multiple weighted perceptrons.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The algorithm starts a new perceptron every time an example is wrongly classified, initializing the weights vector with the final weights of the last perceptron.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Each perceptron will also be given another weight corresponding to how many examples do they correctly classify before wrongly classifying one, and at the end the output will be a weighted vote on all perceptrons.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In separable problems, perceptron training can also aim at finding the largest separating margin between the classes.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The so-called perceptron of optimal stability can be determined by means of iterative training and optimization schemes, such as the Min-Over algorithm (Krauth and Mezard, 1987) or the AdaTron (Anlauf and Biehl, 1989)).
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] AdaTron uses the fact that the corresponding quadratic optimization problem is convex.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The perceptron of optimal stability, together with the kernel trick, are the conceptual foundations of the support-vector machine.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] The $\alpha$ -perceptron further used a pre-processing layer of fixed random weights, with thresholded output units.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] This enabled the perceptron to classify analogue patterns, by projecting them into a binary space.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In fact, for a projection space of sufficiently high dimension, patterns can become linearly separable.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Another way to solve nonlinear problems without using multiple layers is to use higher-order networks (sigma-pi unit).
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] In this type of network, each element in the input vector is extended with each pairwise combination of multiplied inputs (second order).
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] This can be extended to an *n*-order network.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] A generalization of the perceptron model is the Receptron that incorporates non-linear interactions between inputs.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] A single receptron is able to classify non-linear Boolean functions.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] It should be kept in mind, however, that the best classifier is not necessarily that which classifies all the training data perfectly.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Indeed, if we had the prior constraint that the data come from equi-variant Gaussian distributions, the linear separation in the input space is optimal, and the nonlinear solution is overfitted.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Other linear classification algorithms include Winnow, support-vector machine, and logistic regression.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Like most other techniques for training linear classifiers, the perceptron generalizes naturally to multiclass classification.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Here, the input x and the output y are drawn from arbitrary sets.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] A feature representation function $f(x,y)$ maps each possible input/output pair to a finite-dimensional real-valued feature vector.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Learning again iterates over the examples, predicting an output for each, leaving the weights unchanged when the predicted output matches the target, and changing them when it does not.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] This multiclass feedback formulation reduces to the original perceptron when x is a real-valued vector, y is chosen from $\{0,1\}$ , and $f(x,y)=yx$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] For certain problems, input/output representations and features can be chosen so that $\mathrm {argmax} _{y}f(x,y)\cdot w$ can be found efficiently even though y is chosen from a very large or even infinite set.
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] Since 2002, perceptron training has become popular in the field of natural language processing for such tasks as part-of-speech tagging and syntactic parsing (Collins, 2002).
[src:online-learning-theory/perceptron] It has also been applied to large-scale machine learning problems in a distributed computing setting.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] The basic idea behind stochastic approximation can be traced back to the Robbins–Monro algorithm of the 1950s.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Today, stochastic gradient descent has become an important optimization method in machine learning.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Both statistical estimation and machine learning consider the problem of minimizing an objective function that has the form of a sum: $Q(w)={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}Q_{i}(w),$ where the parameter w that minimizes $Q(w)$ is to be estimated.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Each summand function $Q_{i}$ is typically associated with the i -th observation in the data set (used for training).
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In classical statistics, sum-minimization problems arise in least squares and in maximum-likelihood estimation (for independent observations).
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] The general class of estimators that arise as minimizers of sums are called M-estimators.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, in statistics, it has been long recognized that requiring even local minimization is too restrictive for some problems of maximum-likelihood estimation.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Therefore, contemporary statistical theorists often consider stationary points of the likelihood function (or zeros of its derivative, the score function, and other estimating equations).
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] The sum-minimization problem also arises for empirical risk minimization.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] There, $Q_{i}(w)$ is the value of the loss function at i -th example, and $Q(w)$ is the empirical risk.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In many cases, the summand functions have a simple form that enables inexpensive evaluations of the sum-function and the sum gradient.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] For example, in statistics, one-parameter exponential families allow economical function-evaluations and gradient-evaluations.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, in other cases, evaluating the sum-gradient may require expensive evaluations of the gradients from all summand functions.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] When the training set is enormous and no simple formulas exist, evaluating the sums of gradients becomes very expensive, because evaluating the gradient requires evaluating all the summand functions' gradients.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] To economize on the computational cost at every iteration, stochastic gradient descent samples a subset of summand functions at every step.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is very effective in the case of large-scale machine learning problems.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In stochastic (or "on-line") gradient descent, the true gradient of $Q(w)$ is approximated by a gradient at a single sample: $w:=w-\eta \,\nabla Q_{i}(w).$ As the algorithm sweeps through the training set, it performs the above update for each training sample.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Several passes can be made over the training set until the algorithm converges.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] If this is done, the data can be shuffled for each pass to prevent cycles.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Typical implementations may use an adaptive learning rate so that the algorithm converges.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] A compromise between computing the true gradient and the gradient at a single sample is to compute the gradient against more than one training sample (called a "mini-batch") at each step.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] This can perform significantly better than "true" stochastic gradient descent described, because the code can make use of vectorization libraries rather than computing each step separately as was first shown in where it was called "the bunch-mode back-propagation algorithm".
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] It may also result in smoother convergence, as the gradient computed at each step is averaged over more training samples.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] The convergence of stochastic gradient descent has been analyzed using the theories of convex minimization and of stochastic approximation.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is in fact a consequence of the Robbins–Siegmund theorem.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is the key difference between stochastic gradient descent and batched gradient descent.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In general, given a linear regression ${\hat {y}}=\sum _{k\in 1:m}w_{k}x_{k}$ problem, stochastic gradient descent behaves differently when $m<n$ (underparameterized) and $m\geq n$ (overparameterized).
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In the overparameterized case, stochastic gradient descent converges to $\arg \min _{w:w^{T}x_{k}=y_{k}\forall k\in 1:n}\|w-w_{0}\|$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] That is, SGD converges to the interpolation solution with minimum distance from the starting $w_{0}$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] This is true even when the learning rate remains constant.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In the underparameterized case, SGD does not converge if learning rate remains constant.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In 1951, Herbert Robbins and Sutton Monro introduced the earliest stochastic approximation methods, preceding stochastic gradient descent.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Building on this work one year later, Jack Kiefer and Jacob Wolfowitz published an optimization algorithm very close to stochastic gradient descent, using central differences as an approximation of the gradient.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Later in the 1950s, Frank Rosenblatt used SGD to optimize his perceptron model, demonstrating the first applicability of stochastic gradient descent to neural networks.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Backpropagation was first described in 1986, with stochastic gradient descent being used to efficiently optimize parameters across neural networks with multiple hidden layers.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Soon after, another improvement was developed: mini-batch gradient descent, where small batches of data are substituted for single samples.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In 1997, the practical performance benefits from vectorization achievable with such small batches were first explored, paving the way for efficient optimization in machine learning.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] As of 2023, this mini-batch approach remains the norm for training neural networks, balancing the benefits of stochastic gradient descent with gradient descent.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] By the 1980s, momentum had already been introduced, and was added to SGD optimization techniques in 1986.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, these optimization techniques assumed constant hyperparameters, i.e. a fixed learning rate and momentum parameter.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In the 2010s, adaptive approaches to applying SGD with a per-parameter learning rate were introduced with AdaGrad (for "Adaptive Gradient") in 2011 and RMSprop (for "Root Mean Square Propagation") in 2012.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In 2014, Adam (for "Adaptive Moment Estimation") was published, applying the adaptive approaches of RMSprop to momentum; many improvements and branches of Adam were then developed such as Adadelta, Adagrad, AdamW, and Adamax.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Within machine learning, approaches to optimization in 2023 are dominated by Adam-derived optimizers, TensorFlow and PyTorch, by far the most popular machine learning libraries, as of 2023 largely only include Adam-derived optimizers, as well as predecessors to Adam such as RMSprop and classic SGD.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] PyTorch also partially supports limited-memory BFGS, a line-search method, but only for single-device setups without parameter groups.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Stochastic gradient descent is a popular algorithm for training a wide range of models in machine learning, including (linear) support vector machines, logistic regression (see, e.g., Vowpal Wabbit) and graphical models.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] When combined with the backpropagation algorithm, it is the *de facto* standard algorithm for training artificial neural networks.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Its use has been also reported in the Geophysics community, specifically to applications of Full Waveform Inversion (FWI).
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Stochastic gradient descent competes with the L-BFGS algorithm, which is also widely used.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Stochastic gradient descent has been used since at least 1960 for training linear regression models, originally under the name ADALINE.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Another stochastic gradient descent algorithm is the least mean squares (LMS) adaptive filter.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Many improvements on the basic stochastic gradient descent algorithm have been proposed and used.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In particular, in machine learning, the need to set a learning rate (step size) has been recognized as problematic.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Setting this parameter too high can cause the algorithm to diverge; setting it too low makes it slow to converge.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] A conceptually simple extension of stochastic gradient descent makes the learning rate a decreasing function ηt of the iteration number t, giving a *learning rate schedule*, so that the first iterations cause large changes in the parameters, while the later ones do only fine-tuning.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Such schedules have been known since the work of MacQueen on k-means clustering.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Practical guidance on choosing the step size in several variants of SGD is given by Spall.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] As mentioned earlier, classical stochastic gradient descent is generally sensitive to learning rate η.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Fast convergence requires large learning rates but this may induce numerical instability.
