[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] As an example, consider least squares with features $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}\in \mathbb {R} ^{p}$ and observations $y_{1},\ldots ,y_{n}\in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Note that x could have "1" as the first element to include an intercept.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] where i is uniformly sampled between 1 and n .
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Although theoretical convergence of this procedure happens under relatively mild assumptions, in practice the procedure can be quite unstable.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In particular, when $\eta$ is misspecified so that $I-\eta x_{i}x_{i}'$ has large absolute eigenvalues with high probability, the procedure may diverge numerically within a few iterations.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] This procedure will remain numerically stable virtually for all $\eta$ as the learning rate is now normalized.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Such comparison between classical and implicit stochastic gradient descent in the least squares problem is very similar to the comparison between least mean squares (LMS) and normalized least mean squares filter (NLMS).
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Even though a closed-form solution for ISGD is only possible in least squares, the procedure can be efficiently implemented in a wide range of models.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Specifically, suppose that $Q_{i}(w)$ depends on w only through a linear combination with features $x_{i}$ , so that we can write $\nabla _{w}Q_{i}(w)=-q(x_{i}'w)x_{i}$ , where $q()\in \mathbb {R}$ may depend on $x_{i},y_{i}$ as well but not on w except through $x_{i}'w$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Least squares obeys this rule, and so does logistic regression, and most generalized linear models.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In such settings, ISGD is simply implemented as follows.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] The scaling factor $\xi ^{\ast }\in \mathbb {R}$ can be found through the bisection method since in most regular models, such as the aforementioned generalized linear models, function $q()$ is decreasing, and thus the search bounds for $\xi ^{\ast }$ are $[\min(0,f(0)),\max(0,f(0))]$ .
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Further proposals include the *momentum method* or the *heavy ball method*, which in ML context appeared in Rumelhart, Hinton and Williams' paper on backpropagation learning and borrowed the idea from Soviet mathematician Boris Polyak's 1964 article on solving functional equations.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] The name momentum stems from an analogy to momentum in physics: the weight vector w , thought of as a particle traveling through parameter space, incurs acceleration from the gradient of the loss ("force").
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Unlike in classical stochastic gradient descent, it tends to keep traveling in the same direction, preventing oscillations.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Momentum has been used successfully by computer scientists in the training of artificial neural networks for several decades.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] The *momentum method* is closely related to underdamped Langevin dynamics, and may be combined with simulated annealing.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In mid-1980s the method was modified by Yurii Nesterov to use the gradient predicted at the next point, and the resulting so-called *Nesterov Accelerated Gradient* was sometimes used in ML in the 2010s.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] ${\bar {w}}={\frac {1}{t}}\sum _{i=0}^{t-1}w_{i}.$ When optimization is done, this averaged parameter vector takes the place of w.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] where $g_{\tau }=\nabla Q_{i}(w)$ , the gradient, at iteration τ.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] $G_{j,j}=\sum _{\tau =1}^{t}g_{\tau ,j}^{2}.$ This vector essentially stores a historical sum of gradient squares by dimension and is updated after every iteration.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] The formula for an update is now $w:=w-\eta \,\mathrm {diag} (G)^{-{\frac {1}{2}}}\odot g$ or, written as per-parameter updates, $w_{j}:=w_{j}-{\frac {\eta }{\sqrt {G_{j,j}}}}g_{j}.$ Each {*G*(*i*,*i*)} gives rise to a scaling factor for the learning rate that applies to a single parameter *w**i*.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Since the denominator in this factor, ${\textstyle {\sqrt {G_{i}}}={\sqrt {\sum _{\tau =1}^{t}g_{\tau }^{2}}}}$ is the *ℓ*2 norm of previous derivatives, extreme parameter updates get dampened, while parameters that get few or small updates receive higher learning rates.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] While designed for convex problems, AdaGrad has been successfully applied to non-convex optimization.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] where, $\gamma$ is the forgetting factor.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] The concept of storing the historical gradient as sum of squares is borrowed from Adagrad, but "forgetting" is introduced to solve Adagrad's diminishing learning rates in non-convex problems by gradually decreasing the influence of old data.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] RMSProp has shown good adaptation of learning rate in different applications.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] RMSProp can be seen as a generalization of Rprop and is capable to work with mini-batches as well opposed to only full-batches.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] 0.999) are the forgetting factors for gradients and second moments of gradients, respectively.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Squaring and square-rooting is done element-wise.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] As the exponential moving averages of the gradient $m_{w}^{(t)}$ and the squared gradient $v_{w}^{(t)}$ are initialized with a vector of 0's, there would be a bias towards zero in the first training iterations.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] The initial proof establishing the convergence of Adam was incomplete, and subsequent analysis has revealed that Adam does not converge for all convex objectives.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Despite this, *Adam* continues to be used due to its strong performance in practice.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] The popularity of *Adam* inspired many variants and enhancements.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Even though sign-based optimization goes back to the aforementioned *Rprop*, in 2018 researchers tried to simplify Adam by removing the magnitude of the stochastic gradient from being taken into account and only considering its sign.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] This results in a significantly lower communication cost of transferring gradients from workers to the parameter server.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In this sense, it serves to better compress the gradient information, while having comparable convergence to standard SGD.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Backtracking line search is another variant of gradient descent.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] All of the below are sourced from the mentioned link.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] It is based on a condition known as the Armijo–Goldstein condition.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Both methods allow learning rates to change at each iteration; however, the manner of the change is different.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Backtracking line search uses function evaluations to check Armijo's condition, and in principle the loop in the algorithm for determining the learning rates can be long and unknown in advance.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Adaptive SGD does not need a loop in determining learning rates.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] On the other hand, adaptive SGD does not guarantee the "descent property" – which Backtracking line search enjoys – which is that $f(x_{n+1})\leq f(x_{n})$ for all n.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] If the gradient of the cost function is globally Lipschitz continuous, with Lipschitz constant L, and learning rate is chosen of the order 1/L, then the standard version of SGD is a special case of backtracking line search.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] A stochastic analogue of the standard (deterministic) Newton–Raphson algorithm (a "second-order" method) provides an asymptotically optimal or near-optimal form of iterative optimization in the setting of stochastic approximation.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] A method that uses direct measurements of the Hessian matrices of the summands in the empirical risk function was developed by Byrd, Hansen, Nocedal, and Singer.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] However, directly determining the required Hessian matrices for optimization may not be possible in practice.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Practical and theoretically sound methods for second-order versions of SGD that do not require direct Hessian information are given by Spall and others.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] (A less efficient method based on finite differences, instead of simultaneous perturbations, is given by Ruppert.) Another approach to the approximation Hessian matrix is replacing it with the Fisher information matrix, which transforms usual gradient to natural.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] These methods not requiring direct Hessian information are based on either values of the summands in the above empirical risk function or values of the gradients of the summands (i.e., the SGD inputs).
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] In particular, second-order optimality is asymptotically achievable without direct calculation of the Hessian matrices of the summands in the empirical risk function.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] This approximation is only valid on a finite time-horizon in the following sense: assume that all the coefficients ${\textstyle Q_{i}}$ are sufficiently smooth.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Let ${\textstyle T>0}$ and ${\textstyle g:\mathbb {R} ^{d}\to \mathbb {R} }$ be a sufficiently smooth test function.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] where ${\textstyle \mathbb {E} }$ denotes taking the expectation with respect to the random choice of indices in the stochastic gradient descent scheme.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] Since this approximation does not capture the random fluctuations around the mean behavior of stochastic gradient descent solutions to stochastic differential equations (SDEs) have been proposed as limiting objects.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] However this SDE only approximates the one-point motion of stochastic gradient descent.
[src:online-learning-theory/stochastic-gradient-descent] For an approximation of the stochastic flow one has to consider SDEs with infinite-dimensional noise.
[src:online-learning-theory/weighted-majority-algorithm] In machine learning, **weighted majority algorithm (WMA)** is a meta learning algorithm used to construct a compound algorithm from a pool of prediction algorithms, which could be any type of learning algorithms, classifiers, or even real human experts.
[src:online-learning-theory/weighted-majority-algorithm] The algorithm assumes that we have no prior knowledge about the accuracy of the algorithms in the pool, but there are sufficient reasons to believe that one or more will perform well.
[src:online-learning-theory/weighted-majority-algorithm] Assume that the problem is a binary decision problem.
[src:online-learning-theory/weighted-majority-algorithm] To construct the compound algorithm, a positive weight is given to each of the algorithms in the pool.
[src:online-learning-theory/weighted-majority-algorithm] The compound algorithm then collects weighted votes from all the algorithms in the pool, and gives the prediction that has a higher vote.
[src:online-learning-theory/weighted-majority-algorithm] If the compound algorithm makes a mistake, the algorithms in the pool that contributed to the wrong predicting will be discounted by a certain ratio β where 0<β<1.
[src:online-learning-theory/weighted-majority-algorithm] if one algorithm in $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ makes at most $\mathbf {m}$ mistakes.
[src:online-learning-theory/weighted-majority-algorithm] There are many variations of the weighted majority algorithm to handle different situations, like shifting targets, infinite pools, or randomized predictions.
[src:online-learning-theory/weighted-majority-algorithm] The core mechanism remains similar, with the final performances of the compound algorithm bounded by a function of the performance of the **specialist** (best performing algorithm) in the pool.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] The **winnow algorithm** is a technique from machine learning for learning a linear classifier from labeled examples.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] It is very similar to the perceptron algorithm.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] However, the perceptron algorithm uses an additive weight-update scheme, while Winnow uses a multiplicative scheme that allows it to perform much better when many dimensions are irrelevant (hence its name winnow).
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] It is a simple algorithm that scales well to high-dimensional data.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] During training, Winnow is shown a sequence of positive and negative examples.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] From these it learns a decision hyperplane that can then be used to label novel examples as positive or negative.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] The algorithm can also be used in the online learning setting, where the learning and the classification phase are not clearly separated.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] The basic algorithm, Winnow1, is as follows.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] The instance space is $X=\{0,1\}^{n}$ , that is, each instance is described as a set of Boolean-valued features.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] The algorithm maintains non-negative weights $w_{i}$ for $i\in \{1,\ldots ,n\}$ , which are initially set to 1, one weight for each feature.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] Here $\Theta$ is a real number that is called the *threshold*.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] Together with the weights, the threshold defines a dividing hyperplane in the instance space.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] Good bounds are obtained if $\Theta =n/2$ (see below).
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] There are many variations to this basic approach.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] *Winnow2* is similar except that in the demotion step the weights are divided by α instead of being set to 0.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] *Balanced Winnow* maintains two sets of weights, and thus two hyperplanes.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] This can then be generalized for multi-label classification.
[src:online-learning-theory/winnow-algorithm] In certain circumstances, it can be shown that the number of mistakes Winnow makes as it learns has an upper bound that is independent of the number of instances with which it is presented.
